The accompanying drawings, which are incorporated in and constitute a part of this specification, illustrate an embodiment of the invention and, together with the description, explain the objects, advantages and principles of the invention. In the drawings,


FIG. 1 is a block diagram of a conventional system containing a multimode pump source coupled to a primary fiber via a single traditional coupler;


FIG. 2 is a block diagram of a system that recovers a portion of the lost pump power;


FIG. 3 is a diagram of a twin coupler system consistent with the principles of the present invention;


FIG. 4A is a diagram depicting a cross-sectional view of the primary fiber of FIG. 3;


FIG. 4B is a graph of the different indexes of refraction of the primary fiber of FIG. 3;


FIG. 5A is a diagram depicting a cross-sectional view of the pump fiber of FIG. 3;


FIG. 5B is a graph of the different indexes of refraction of the pump fiber of FIG. 3;


FIGS. 6A-6D are flow charts describing a method for manufacturing the twin coupler system consistent with the principles of the present invention;


FIG. 7 is a block diagram of a simplified version of the twin coupler system of FIG. 3;


FIG. 8 is a block diagram of the equipment used for manufacturing a first coupler of FIG. 3;


FIGS. 9A and 9B are graphs depicting temperature and speed profiles, respectively, for the fusion and tapering operations to produce the first coupler;


FIG. 10 is a block diagram of the equipment used for manufacturing a second coupler of FIG. 3; and


FIGS. 11A and 11B are graphs depicting temperature and speed profiles, respectively, for the fusion and tapering operations to produce the second coupler.
